{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01ChbeFibi4SqJayVy7Y7QYg","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: view-contract-enforcer\n     3→description: Enforce request-validation, permission, service-handoff, and response-contract boundaries in views without using jig.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# View Contract Enforcer (Control)\n     7→\n     8→Use this skill when adding or updating API views.\n     9→Implement the file edits directly. Do not return a checklist-only response.\n    10→\n    11→## Required Variables\n    12→\n    13→- `view_name`\n    14→- `http_method`\n    15→- `request_schema_name`\n    16→- `response_schema_name`\n    17→- `service_symbol`\n    18→- `url_path`\n    19→- `url_name`\n    20→- `test_name`\n    21→- `test_url`\n    22→\n    23→## Required Output Contract\n    24→\n    25→1. Modify `schemas.py`, `views.py`, `urls.py`, and `tests/test_views.py`.\n    26→2. In `schemas.py`:\n    27→- add the request serializer class using the provided `request_schema_name`, with `correlation_id = serializers.CharField(required=False, allow_blank=True)`\n    28→- add the response serializer class using the provided `response_schema_name`, with `id = serializers.IntegerField()` and `status = serializers.CharField()`\n    29→3. In `views.py`:\n    30→- import the provided request and response schema names from `.schemas`\n    31→- import the provided `service_symbol` from `.services`\n    32→- define `@api_view([http_method])` using the provided method literal\n    33→- define the view function using the provided `view_name`\n    34→- assign `request_contract = RequestSchemaName(data=request.data)` using the provided request schema class\n    35→- call `request_contract.is_valid(raise_exception=True)`\n    36→- assign `payload = request_contract.validated_data`\n    37→- assign `result = service_symbol(pk=pk, payload=payload)` using the provided service symbol\n    38→- assign `response_contract = ResponseSchemaName(result)` using the provided response schema class\n    39→- return `Response(response_contract.data, status=200)`\n    40→4. In `urls.py`, add a path entry using `api/` plus the provided `url_path`, pointing to the provided `view_name`, with the provided `url_name`.\n    41→5. In `tests/test_views.py`, add the provided `test_name` method that posts to the provided `test_url` with `{\"correlation_id\": \"h2h\"}` and asserts the status code is in `[200, 400, 401, 404]`.\n    42→6. Use the exact variable names `request_contract`, `payload`, and `response_contract`.\n    43→\n    44→## Guardrails\n    45→\n    46→- No domain write logic in view functions.\n    47→- No ad hoc payload parsing that bypasses the request contract.\n    48→- Do not add extra permission decorators or alternate response-contract wiring unless the prompt explicitly asks for them.\n    49→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a4481165-a6ac-45f4-a32d-6f0e1aa99126","uuid":"599345fe-6d99-4380-8af5-b78c5a8b909a"}
